      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@Popeye Not a stupid question! The principle doesn&#39;t change, UUID generation is really random—meaning you can consider the generation of UUIDs to to be independent events from one another. In other words, creating UUIDs from different computers does not change anything, it is <i>incredibly unlikely</i> that a collision will occur. In fact, this is why distributed systems tend to use UUID-like identifiers instead of global sequential identifiers which require locking. Google, Facebook and other big data organisations all use identifiers like them (though, perhaps their length is greater?)"
