    "answer_id" : 24876263,
    "question_id" : 24876188,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>According to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universally_unique_identifier#Random_UUID_probability_of_duplicates\" rel=\"noreferrer\">wikipedia</a>, regarding the probability of duplicates in random UUIDs:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Only after generating 1 billion UUIDs every second for the next 100 years, the probability of creating just one duplicate would be about 50%. Or, to put it another way, the probability of one duplicate would be about 50% if every person on earth owned 600 million UUIDs.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>I guess the same reasoning applies to Java's implementation of UUID. So no, you should not worry about this.</p>\n"
  } ],
